<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="468" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1508,2038]" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1616,1642]" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Central American species, recognized by the combination of moderate size (ca. 
<quantity box="[151,255,1653,1679]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.44" pageId="9" pageNumber="468" unit="mm" value="3.44">3.44 mm</quantity>
), the rather uniformly densely punctate pronotum, except less dense on reliefs, with deep depressions, the distinctly denticulate pronotum lateral margins, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[961,1030,1688,1714]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,192,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-22@24.[151,1435,181,1910]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 5. Hydrochus biexcavatus n. sp. 6. Hydrochus mesoamericanus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4777855" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4777855/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
; described below). This species has a generalized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1817" box="[310,432,1724,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[310,432,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">Hydrochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
habitus; reliable determinations will require dissection of males. The male genitalia are differentiated from other Central American species by the combination of nearly straight paramere tips and the large dorsal membranous area of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="469" pageId="9" pageNumber="468" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1508,2038]" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1832,1858]" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">Description</emphasis>
. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[605,674,1832,1859]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,192,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-22@24.[151,1435,181,1910]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 5. Hydrochus biexcavatus n. sp. 6. Hydrochus mesoamericanus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4777855" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4777855/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Size: 
<typeStatus box="[759,857,1832,1858]" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 3.44/1.53; head width 0.78; pronotum l/w 0.73/0.82; PA 0.78; PB 0.69; elytra 2.38/1.53. Body size moderately large (ca. 
<quantity box="[199,303,1905,1931]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.44" pageId="9" pageNumber="468" unit="mm" value="3.44">3.44 mm</quantity>
). Dorsum dark brown, with very little iridescence, elytra without black spots. Punctation on elytra ca. 2–3x that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae ca. 1–1.5× strial puncture diameter. Interstria 9 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1134,1147,1940,1954]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">th</superScript>
more convex than others, overhanging 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[325,338,1976,1990]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">th</superScript>
interstria. Usual area of callus on 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[731,744,1976,1990]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="468">th</superScript>
weakly raised, moderately elongate, ca. 5 punctures in row on each side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Pronotum slightly wider than long, widest slightly behind anterior margin, narrowed at base, sides sinuate, minutely but distinctly denticulate; anterior margin bisinuate; rather uniformly densely punctate, except less dense on reliefs; depressions deep.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Elytra with spaces between strial punctures ca. 0.5–1x their diameter; apices rather sharply conjointly rounded in dorsal view, in lateral view outer margin with moderate angulation.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Ventral characters: Mentum coarsely densely punctate, with large median fovea. Submentum punctate, without foveae. Legs brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[377,446,403,430]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–6" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1934,1958]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,192,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-22@24.[151,1435,181,1910]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 5–6. Habitus and male genitalia of holotypes. 5. Hydrochus biexcavatus n. sp. 6. Hydrochus mesoamericanus n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4777855" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4777855/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) general characters: paramere tips slender and pointed, in lateral view narrower than in dorsal/ventral views and sharply pointed, in dorsal/ventral views with medial margins at apex parallel or nearly so, then arcuate away from midline, narrow proximal to plsa; aedeagus in dorsal/ventral views wide in distal ½, only slightly wider in proximal ½, greatest width as ca. midlength; in lateral view slightly wider in proximal ½, and much wider in membranous distal 1/2; lateral margins of aedeagus sclerotized; basal piece slightly shorter than parameres, tapering proximally, orifice strongly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Dorsal surface: pdmm widely separated, sinuate; adbl large; adtl as about distal 1/3; paramere tips without dorsal sclerotized ridge.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" box="[199,1103,691,717]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Ventral surface: pvmm approximating lateral margin of aedeagus; avtl near base.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,927,727,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,753]" box="[199,927,727,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,727,753]" pageId="10" pageNumber="469">Etymology.</emphasis>
